addr="ca-001J"
title="Contracting sequence">Contracting sequence</fr:link> of nonempty <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-000P.xml"
addr="ca-000P"
title="Closed Subset">Closed Subset</fr:link>s of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. For each index <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, select <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  E_{n}]]></fr:tex>. We claim this <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-001D.xml"
addr="ca-001D"
title="Cauchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</fr:link>. For each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex>, there is an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> suchthat <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathop {\textrm {diam}}\nolimits (E_{N})<\varepsilon ]]></fr:tex>. Since this is descending, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\geq  N]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  E_{N}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{m}\in  E_{N}]]></fr:tex>, and therefore
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[d(x_{n},x_{m})\leq \mathop {\textrm {diam}}\nolimits (E_{N})<\varepsilon .]]></fr:tex>
Hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> is Cauchy. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is complete, this sequence converges to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{n}]]></fr:tex> is closed for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{k})_{k\geq  n}]]></fr:tex> is a convergent sequence in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{n}]]></fr:tex>, by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-001C.xml"
addr="ca-001C"
title="Subset is closed iff all convergent sequences on the subset have limits there">Subset is closed iff all convergent sequences on the subset have limits there</fr:link> the limit <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> belongs to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{n}]]></fr:tex>. Thus
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[x\in \bigcap ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}.]]></fr:tex>
It is impossible for the intersection to contain two points <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, because if it did, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\lim _{n\to \infty }\mathop {\textrm {diam}}\nolimits (E_{n})\geq  d(u,v)>0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Assume that for any contracting sequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(E_{n})]]></fr:tex> of nonempty closed subsets of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, there is a point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigcap ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}=\{x\}]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> be a Cauchy sequence in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. For each index <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, define <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{n}]]></fr:tex> to be the closure of the nonempty set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_{k}\mid  k\geq  n\}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(E_{n})]]></fr:tex> is a descending sequence of nonempty closed sets. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> is Cauchy, the sequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(E_{n})]]></fr:tex> is contracting. So by assumption there is a point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\bigcap ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}=\{x\}.]]></fr:tex>
For each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is a limit point of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_{k}\mid  k\geq  n\}]]></fr:tex>. Hence we may inductively select a strictly increasing set of integers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{n_{k}\}]]></fr:tex> such that for each index <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[d(x,x_{n_{k}})<1/ k]]></fr:tex>. The subsequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n_{k}})]]></fr:tex> converges to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> is Cauchy, the whole sequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n})]]></fr:tex> converges to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>. Therefore <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is complete.</fr:p><html:span
